ion-making. On the other, it's striking to hear Zuckerberg reckoning with t=
he full weight of the responsibility that he has accepted. The answer to &q=
uot;who chose me&quot; is of course Zuckerberg himself, who has ruthlessly =
pursued growth around the world, bought up or attempted to strangle every c=
ompetitor, and worked to cement his total and individual control over the c=
ompany (https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2017/09/shareholders-force-zuck=
erberg-to-give-up-plan-for-non-voting-shares/).

Given these facts, it's perhaps comforting that Zuckerberg says he hopes to=
 avoid &quot;making content policy decisions for people around the world.&q=
uot; But who can be trusted to make those content policy decisions, and who=
 ensures that they are evenly enforced, remains a significant challenge.

At the Times, Kevin Roose asked Zuckerberg (https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03=
/21/technology/mark-zuckerberg-q-and-a.html) how he felt about the situatio=
n in Myanmar, where the United Nations has blamed Facebook for spreading ha=
te speech that has incited violence against the minority Rohingya populatio=
n. Elsewhere in his interviews, the CEO came across as warm and empathetic.=
 But his response here struck me as rather cold:

It=E2=80=99s certainly true that, over the course of Facebook, I=E2=80=99ve=
 made all kinds of different mistakes, whether that=E2=80=99s technical mis=
takes or business mistakes or hiring mistakes. We=E2=80=99ve launched produ=
ct after product that didn=E2=80=99t work. I spend most of my time looking =
forward, trying to figure out how to solve the issues that people are havin=
g today, because I think that=E2=80=99s what people in our community would =
want.Technical mistakes, business mistakes, hiring mistakes: errors of thes=
e kind are much less consequential, in the long run, of the murders of inno=
cent people caught up in the spread of viral hoaxes and calls for violence.=
 Zuckerberg's interview tour strikes me as a net positive for the company: =
it seemed to slow the bleeding around the Cambridge Analytica scandal, with=
out quite stopping it.

But as I noted here yesterday, Facebook is currently confronting multiple c=
rises. Today, data privacy is on everyone's mind. But once that fades, the =
Rohingya won't be better off. Nor will the Muslim minority in Sri Lanka, wh=
ere Facebook recently had to temporarily shut down its service in response =
to a wave of violence being carried out using Facebook-owned apps.=C2=A0

It feels odd to describe challenges like these in the terms of &quot;what t=
he community wants.&quot; &quot;I spend most of my time looking forward,&qu=
ot; Zuckerberg said, and I wonder whether if he would not be better served =
in this moment by simply looking around.


